'''Arthur Versluis''' (born 1959) is a professor and Department Chair of Religious Studies in the College of Arts & Letters at Michigan State University.<ref group=web>[http://www.religiousstudies.msu.edu/index.php/faculty/ Michigan State University, Religious Studues Faculty]</ref><ref group=web>[http://arthurversluis.com/?page_id=29 arthurversluis.com, ''About'']</ref>
==Academic career== Versluis did his Ph.D research at the University of Michigan, Ann Arbor. His thesis ''Ex oriente lux: American Transcendentalism and the Orient'' (1990)<ref group=web>[http://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/handle/2027.42/104316 Arthur Versluis, ''''Ex oriente lux'']</ref> was published in 1993 as ''American Transcendentalism and Asian Religions''.<ref group=web name="MSU">[http://www.religiousstudies.msu.edu/index.php/faculty/arthur-versluis/ Michigan State University, ''Arthus Versluis'']</ref>
==Research topics== Versluis' research focuses on [[western esotericism]] and [[magic (paranormal)|magic]], with a special interest in the influence of [[Platonism]] on western mysticism and American [[Transcendentalism]].<ref group=web name="AV-7Q">[https://scholarblogs.emory.edu/sacredmatters/2015/01/12/seven-questions-for-arthur-versluis/ ''American Gurus: Seven Questions for Arthur Versluis''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417164207/https://scholarblogs.emory.edu/sacredmatters/2015/01/12/seven-questions-for-arthur-versluis/ |date=April 17, 2016 }}</ref>
===Transcendentalism and American esotericism=== {{See also|Neo-Advaita|Subitism}}
Versluis has published a "trilogy" on American Transcendentalism and the development of western esotericism, namely ''American Transcendentalism and Asian Religions'' (1993), ''The Esoteric Origins of the American Renaissance'' (2001), and ''American Gurus: From Transcendentalism to New Age Religion'' (2014). In these publications, he describes the development of American Transcendentalism and its influence on western esotericism, including the contemporary phenomenon of "immediatist gurus", who promise instant enlightenment.<ref group=web name="AV-7Q" />
In ''American Transcendentalism and Asian Religions'', Versluis describes the influence of Asian religions on European Romanticism and on American Transcendentalism.{{sfn|Versluis|2001|p=3}} In the early 19th century, these Asian religions were introduced to the western culture, and texts like the [[Bhagavad Gita]] and the [[Upanishads]] had a great impact on the Transcendental movement, and influential members like [[Ralph Waldo Emerson|Emerson]] and [[Thoreau]].{{sfn|Versluis|2001|p=3}} But Transcendentalism was also influenced by [[western esotericism]], a topic which until recently received little attention in the academia.{{sfn|Versluis|2001|p=3}}{{refn|group=note|See also Elizabeth De Michelis (2005), ''A History of Modern Yoga'', for this neglected influence on the development of a global spirituality.}}
In ''The Esoteric Origins of the American Renaissance'' Versluis investigates the influence of western esotericism on the mid-19th [[American Renaissance]]. Versluis regards his ''The Esoteric Origins'' as a pioneering study in this discipline.{{sfn|Versluis|2001|p=3}}
In ''American Gurus: From Transcendentalism to New Age Religion'', Versluis describes the emergence of immediatist gurus: gurus who are not connected to any of the traditional religions, and promise instant enlightenment and liberation.{{sfn|Versluis|2014|p=1,2}} These include [[Eckhart Tolle]], [[Ram Dass]], [[Adi Da]], and [[Andrew Cohen (spiritual teacher)|Andrew Cohen]].{{sfn|Versluis|2014|p=1}} "Immediatism" refers to "a religious assertion of spontaneous, direct, unmediated spiritual insight into reality (typically with little or no prior training), which some term [[Enlightenment (spirituality)|"enlightenment"]]."{{sfn|Versluis|2014|p=2}} According to Versluis, immediatism is typical for Americans, who want "the fruit of religion, but not its obligations."<ref group=web name="AV-7Q" /> Although immediatism has its roots in European culture and history{{sfn|Versluis|2014|p=2}} as far back as [[Platonism]],{{sfn|Versluis|2014|p=3}} and also includes [[Perennial philosophy|Perennialism]],{{sfn|Versluis|2014|p=4}} Versluis points to [[Ralph Waldo Emerson]] as its key ancestor,{{sfn|Versluis|2014|p=2}} who "emphasized the possibility of immediate, direct spiritual knowledge and power."{{sfn|Versluis|2014|p=3}}
===Christian Theosophy=== Another "trilogy" deals with [[Christian theosophy]], and includes ''Theosophia'' (1994), ''Wisdom’s Children: A Christian Esoteric Tradition'' (1999), and ''Wisdom’s Book: The Sophia Anthology'' (2000).<ref group=web name="MSU" />
==Journals and associations== Versluis is an editor of the ''Journal for the Study of Radicalism'', and founding editor of ''Esoterica'', which started as a journal, and is now a biannual print book series, ''Studies in Esotericism''.<ref group=web name="MSU" /> Versluis is also the founding president of the ''Association for the Study of Esotericism''.<ref group=web name="MSU" />
